SIMPLE: prose
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prose
<hw>Prose</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>prose</ets>, L.
<ets>prosa</ets>, fr. <ets>prorsus</ets>, <ets>prosus</ets>, straight
forward, straight on, for <ets>proversus</ets>; <ets>pro</ets> forward +
<ets>versus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>vertere</ets> to turn. See
<er>Verse</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The ordinary language of men in
speaking or writing; language not cast in poetical measure or rhythm; --
contradistinguished from <xex>verse</xex>, or <xex>metrical
composition</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I speak in <qex>prose</qex>, and let him rymes make.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Things unattempted yet in <qex>prose</qex> or rhyme.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I wish our clever young poets would remember my homely definitions
of <qex>prose</qex> and poetry, that is; <qex>prose</qex> -- words in
their best order; poetry -- the best order.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, language which evinces little imagination or
animation; dull and commonplace discourse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>A hymn with no regular meter,
sometimes introduced into the Mass. See <er>Sequence</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prose</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prose
<hw>Prose</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or
composed of, prose; not in verse; <as>as, <ex>prose</ex>
composition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Possessing or exhibiting unpoetical characteristics;
plain; dull; prosaic; <as>as, the <ex>prose</ex> duties of
life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prose</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Prose
<hw>Prose</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Prosed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Prosing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To write in
prose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To write or repeat in a dull, tedious, or prosy
way.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prose</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Prose
<hw>Prose</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To write
prose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Prosing</qex> or versing, but chiefly this latter.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prosector</ent>⟦br⟧
